Selection Sort

Selection Sort is a simple comparison-based sorting algorithm. It is generally considered better than Bubble Sort because it performs fewer swaps.

How it works:

The list is divided into two parts: the sorted part at the left end and the unsorted part at the right end.

Initially, the sorted part is empty and the unsorted part is the entire list.

The algorithm proceeds by finding the smallest (minimum) element in the unsorted sublist.

It swaps this smallest element with the leftmost unsorted element (putting it in sorted order).

It then moves the sublist boundaries one element to the right.

Complexity:

Time Complexity: O(n^2) - It uses nested loops, so it is still slow for large lists.

Space Complexity: O(1) - It sorts in place.